  "prompt": "Why do weights of assets in a portfolio turn negative when I short sell that asset?",
  "response": "When you short sell an asset, you essentially borrow that asset and sell it with the expectation that its price will decline, allowing you to buy it back at a lower price to return to the lender. In terms of portfolio weights, short selling means you are taking a negative position on that asset. Here's why this results in negative weights for assets in your portfolio:\n\n1. **Definition of Portfolio Weights**: Portfolio weights are typically defined as the proportion of the total portfolio value that is invested in each asset. When you own an asset, its weight is positive because you have invested in it.\n\n2. **Short Selling Mechanism**: When you short sell an asset, you create a liability because you owe the borrowed shares back. In this case, the value of the short position represents a bet against the asset. You are effectively \"selling\" the asset that you do not own, financing it by a margin or from the cash obtained from the sale.\n\n3. **Negative Weight Calculation**: In portfolio theory, the weight of the shorted asset is calculated as the value of the short position (which is a liability) divided by the total portfolio value. Since the short position is treated as a negative investment (you have borrowed and sold the asset), the weight becomes negative:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Weight}_{\\text{short asset}} = \\frac{-\\text{value of short position}}{\\text{total portfolio value}}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Impact on Portfolio Composition**: By short selling, you increase exposure to other assets or cash, effectively allowing you to hedge against market movements. The negative weight reflects your expectation of a price decline in the shorted asset.\n\nIn summary, when you short sell an asset, you take on a liability that is reflected in your portfolio as a negative weight, indicating that you're betting against the performance of that asset.",
